<p>From what I understand, <code>this</code> inside of a function refers to the object invoking the function. So, for instance, in</p>  <pre><code>myObj = { name : "Charlie", getType : function() { return typeof(this); } };  console.log(myObj.getType());  </code></pre>  <p>the object invoking the function <code>getType</code> is <code>myObj</code> and therefore <code>typeof(this)</code> is <code>typeof(myObj)</code>.</p>  <p>Why, then, do I always see <code>$(this)</code> inside jQuery functions? For instance, in</p>  <pre><code>$('.not-taller-than-50-pixels').each(function() {      if ($(this).height() &gt; 50) $(this).height(50); }); </code></pre>  <p>doesn't <code>$('.not-taller-than-50-pixels')</code> return an array of jQuery objects and so inside the <code>each</code> the invoking function is a jQuery object and so <code>this</code> would refer to that jQuery object and I can simply write <code>if (this.height() &gt; 50) this.height(50);</code> ???</p>